 The iconic embroidered shirt or blouse, the [[vyshyvanka]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Ukrainian Vyshyvanka (embroidered shirt) |url=http://unknownukraine.com/ukrainian-vyshyvanka/ |website=Unknown Ukraine |access-date=7 March 2022}}</ref> is the most recognizable part of Ukrainian national costume, and even has its own public celebration in May.<ref name="Unian_Vysh">{{cite web |title=Ukrainians celebrating Vyshyvanka Day on May 20 |url=https://www.unian.info/society/vyshyvanka-day-ukrainians-worldwide-praise-one-of-national-symbols-on-may-20-11426332.html |website=Unian |access-date=7 March 2022}}</ref> For men, traditional dress also includes [[kozhukh]], [[kontusz]], [[Å¼upan]] and [[sharovary]]. For women, traditional dress includes [[kozhushanka]], [[ochipok]] for married women, and [[Ukrainian wreath]] for unmarried girls. Garments are made using elaborate structural design, complicated weaving techniques, extensive embroidery, and [[Cutwork|cutwork needlework]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2022}}

 ====Weaving and embroidery====
