===Museums and libraries===
{{Main|Western European paintings in Ukrainian museums}}
There are nearly 5,000 different [[museums in Ukraine]],<ref>[http://culture.unian.net/ukr/detail/188753 Ð£ÐIÐÐ - ÐšÑƒÐ»ÑŒÑ‚ÑƒÑ€Ð° - Ð£ÐºÑ€Ð°Ñ—Ð½Ð° â€“ Ð¼ÑƒÐ·ÐµÐ¹Ð½Ð° ÐšÑ€Ð°Ñ—Ð½Ð°<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> including [[National Art Museum of Ukraine]], [[National Historical Museum of Ukraine]], [[Museum of Western and Oriental Art]], [[Ukrainian National Chernobyl Museum]] in Kyiv, [[Lviv National Art Gallery]], [[Poltava Art Museum]], [[Simferopol Art Museum]], and many others of art, history, traditions or dedicated to different issues. Many of these museums are at risk due to the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theartnewspaper.com/2022/03/25/ukraine-culture-in-peril | title=Culture in the crossfire: Ukraine's key monuments and museums at risk of destruction in the war | first=Konstantin | last=Akinsha | newspaper=[[The Art Newspaper]] | date=25 March 2022 | accessdate=26 March 2022 }}</ref>

There are 14 libraries of state significance ([[Vernadsky National Library of Ukraine]], [[National Parliamentary Library of Ukraine]], National historical library of Ukraine in Kyiv, [[Korolenko State Scientific Library]] in Kharkiv, and others), and 45,000 public libraries all over Ukraine. All these institutions own 700 million books.<ref>[http://www.nbuv.gov.ua/portal/libukr.html Ð‘Ñ–Ð±Ð»Ñ–Ð¾Ñ‚ÐµÐºÐ¸ Ñ‚Ð° Ð½Ð°ÑƒÐºÐ¾Ð²Ð¾-Ñ–Ð½Ñ„Ð¾Ñ€Ð¼Ð°Ñ†Ñ–Ð¹Ð½Ñ– Ñ†ÐµÐ½Ñ‚Ñ€Ð¸ Ð£ÐºÑ€Ð°Ñ—Ð½Ð¸<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

====Literature====
{{Main|Ukrainian literature}}

Ukrainian literature had a difficult development because, due to constant foreign domination over [[Ukraine|Ukrainian territories]], there was often a significant difference between the spoken and written language. At times the use of the Ukrainian language was even partly prohibited to be [[Ems Ukaz|printed]]. However, foreign rule by [[Lithuania]], [[Poland]], [[Romania]], [[Russia]], [[Austria-Hungary]], and the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman Turkey]], left behind new words thereby enriching Ukrainian.<ref name="Brit_lang">{{cite web |title=Ukrainian language |url=https://www.britannica.com/topic/Ukrainian-language |website=Britannica |access-date=7 March 2022}}</ref> Despite tsarist and Soviet repression, Ukrainian authors were able to produce a rich literary heritage.<ref name="Brit_lit">{{cite web |title=Ukrainian literature |url=https://www.britannica.com/art/Ukrainian-literature |website=Britannica |access-date=7 March 2022}}</ref>

Many Ukrainians also contributed to the closely related [[Russian literature|literature in Russian language]].<ref name="UIL_lit">{{cite web |title=Ukraine's distinctive Russian-language culture |url=https://ukrainianinstitute.org.uk/ukraines-distinctive-russian-language-culture-an-evening-with-andrey-kurkov/ |website=Ukrainian Institute London |access-date=7 March 2022}}</ref>

